			Egress control and private VM architectre

## Objective - understanding & controlling egress traffic 

- build a clear mental model of how traffic leaves a VM in GCP and validate is through firewall testing 

- understand how traffic leaves VM's in GCP and how firewall rules control putbound traffic

##Key Concepts

- Egress, Traffic leaving the VM ( using Curl )

- Ingress, Traffic coming into the VM ( using ssh from my laptop to the VM)

- Firewall Priority, rules are evaluated by priority, the lower the value
the higher the priority

- Protocol and port matching, firewall rules don't block the internet 
they block specific combinations of
Direction 
Protocol (TCP/UDP/etc)
Port(443,80,22,etc)
Destination Range
Target (tag or instance)

## What i Did Practically 

- SSH'd into my VM
- Ran "curl httpa://ifconfig.me to confirm outboud traffic worked by default
- created and egress rule tp deny for TCP port 443
- Tested HTTPS (blocked)
- Tested HTTP (still worked) 
- Modified the rule to deny all protocols
- confirmed all outbound traffic was blocked 

## What confused me 
- initally made an "Allow" rule instead of a "Deny" rule 

## Mental Model

now i visualize firewall rules as a serires of logical gates 

Traffice leas the VM and Hits the Firewall. The Firewall checks:

1 Does direction match
2 Does target match
3 Does protocl and port match 
4 Does destination match 
5 What is the priority

if all match, the action (Allow or Deny) is applied

Outbound traffice is allowed by default unless Explicitly denied 


